{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_collins_ver01/data/sn84022396/00517173903/1937123001/1137.xml":{"full_text":"THE PUTNAM PATRIOT\nPUBLISHED BY\nTHE PATRIOT PRESS, Incorporated\nKATHERINE C. MACDONALD.~..President\nTHE year that will come to a close at midnight tomorrow will\npuzzle the future historians, who undertake to analyze the\nmotives and account for the unrest, that has marked the pass\ning of its twelve months. Europe, under a systematic Fascist\npolicy of intrigue, is waiting what destiny has in store for it.\nIn the Far East, war in its most ruthless form is horrifying the\ncivilized world. The people of Spain are still in the agony of\nCivil War, and the end is not yet in sight.\nHere in our own country the year that started under such\nfavorable conditions has undergone a business recession, the\ncauses of which are matter of controversy. The President and\nhis advisors, while bidding for the cooperation of business in\ncounteracting the let-down, still show no inclination to modify\nthe policies of drastic reform, to which the administration is\ncommitted. Congress, it is true, is showing some signs of\nhaving a mind of its own. This is a favorable symptom that\nbusiness and government may yet find neutral ground on which\nthe country\u2019s prosperity may forge ahead.\nHere in New England, the business recession has caused\na dislocation of full time operation in many of our industries.\nThis has had its consequent effect on general business. That\nthis halt in the general advance of business progress is tem\nporary is the concensus of opinion among men who are in posi\ntions to know the signs of the times. The beginning of a new\nyear brings with it the hopefulness that comes from a fresh\nstart. The blank page of 1938 is spread before us for our\nwriting on. It is up to the country at large, in a spirit of help\nfulness and unity, to make that chronicle a record of achieve\nment, that will bring prosperity and happiness to all the\npeople. No one can tell what the new year has in store for us.\nWhether for good or evil, however, this country is at its best\nas a united people. The bringing about of that unity calls for\na spirit of cooperation, that will make us truly a nation that\nis many in one.\nKEYREN H. COTTER...\nGEORGE E. CONNELL.\nTreasurer and Business Mgr.\n....Editor\nTHE PASSING OF 1937\nV\nIf.\nPUTNAM CHANGES ITS POLITICS\nWITH the passing of 1937, the government of this city passes\nout of the hands of the Republicans into the keeping of\nits rivals. The administration that relinquishes the reins of\noffice next Monday leaves behind it a record of which it may\nwell be proud. Mayor Murphy\u2019s four years in office have been\na period of achievement in advancing the best interests of\nPutnam that has few parallels in the history of the city. In the\nexpectation of what might be accomplished during another\nterm in office, we were frankly disappointed by his defeat in\nthe December election.\nSo many things affect the electorate\u2019s desire for a change,\nthat an adverse vote for a candidate may not even carry dis\napproval of the things that have been accomplished by the de\nfeated candidate. We feel sure that it was so in the case of\nMayor Murphy. During his two terms he has written himself\nlargely into our municipal history. During four years as maj or\nof Putnam, he was holding a responsible executive position in\none of our largest industries. His holding office was a sacrifice\nin the interest of modern, progressive government tor the city.\nThe double responsibility laid a heavy burden on his shoulders.\nHis name will always be linked with those improvements in the\ncity\u2019s equipment that he pushed with all the \\igoi of his\nenergetic personality. One of the secrets of his capacity for\ngetting things done was that he never did things by halves.\nMavor Murphv, we are sure, will carry back into private life\nthe' good wishes of the people of Putnam. It goes without\nsaying that his interest in the city of which he was the head\n-will not lag. He is an asset and will remain an asset in the\ncounsels of the Republican Party, c\nHarry C. Kelly, who becomes mayor on Monday, will have\nthe opportunity to give the City of Putnam the kind of admin\nistration that its people expect. He will have the cooperation\nof the council and the outcome is in his own hands. To him we\nextend our best wishes, that his administration may measure\nup to the standard of his predecessors.\nTHE REOPENING OF THE BRADLEY\nONCE again the Bradley Theatre is the center of attraction\nto the people of this section. As the pivot around which\nthe gaiety of the city revolves, it has been greatly missed dur\ning the period of its enforced \u201cdarkness.\u201d Its patrons are now\ntreated to changes in the auditorium and equipment that raises\nour motion picture theatre to the level of one of the most at\ntractive and comfortable movie houses to be found outside the\nlarge cities.\nThe management of the Bradley has long contemplated\nthe changes that have now been made. The old theatre tra\ndition that the show must go on in spite of everything and any\nthing keeps putting off extensive alterations to this type ol\nedifice. When the opportunity came to the management, how\never, advantage was taken of it, and it has turned out to e a\nmightv fine job. With the Bradley\u2019s gleaming front once more\nin evidence, we can feel that the night life of Putnam is bad\nto normalcy.\nWOODSTOCK\u2019S THEFT DETECTING SOCIETY\nTHE tradition of older and simpler times is kept ali\\e in^ar\norganization that still meets annually in Woodstock aftei\none hundred and forty-four years of existence. The name o\nthis historical relic is the Woodstock Theft Detecting Society\nIts primary purpose was the detection, capture and pumshmeni\nof horse thieves. It is a curious commentary on the change,\nthat ^me brings about, that an organization brought togethe,\nto curb the stealing of horses should have outlasted the cnmi\nslothing'a bit thrilling in reconstructing th.\nearly exploit, of the soci.\nparticularly vicious form of theft in eariy agmuu\nn,ttes. We can imagine the excitement when the alarm\naounded that a farmer's horse had been stolen. That there\nmounting in hot haste, we can be well assured. Road\nwould be scoured by the indignant band of vigilantes. If th<\nUNDERSTANDING\nOUR\nCHILDREN\nB\u201e\nMargaret Mowry\n(Special to The Patriot)\nI have, among my friends one wh\nmakes not only clevei but useft\nand interesting gifts. How for\ntunate we who receive them feel\nand how we treasure them.\nChildren, in most families havi\nlittle money to spend and present\nfor relatives and friends are ehoset\nI and paid for by their parents. I be\nj Sieve some of the joy of giving i\ntaken away from a child under thesi\ncircumstances, so I have a few sug\ngestions to offer which take litth\ntime to make, and less money, anc\ngives the child a feeling of persona\naccomplishment.\nHow often has mother run fot\nsomething to put under a hot dish\non the table? Mats for this purpose\nare easily made by covering a round\nor square, piece of cardboard with\noil cloth and finishing the edges with\nthe blanket, or simple over and over\nstitch. A set of three, varied in size,\nI makes a very nice gift.\nFather is always looking for an\na^h tray. A new good looking one\nmay be made by pasteing a picture\non the under side of a glass castor\ncup, then cover with blotting or con\nstruction paper. Ordinary paste\nmay be used but rubber cement is\nmore satisfactory. Also, pretty\nmatch cases may be made by paste\ning a picture on top of a penny box\nof matches, the sides being covered\nwith paper of harmonizing colors,\n(The linings of Christmas envelopes\noften prove very attractive*.\nDo you know of someone who likes\nto take particular care of her books?\nA cellophane cover may be made,\n(folded as you do any book cover,)\nand has the advantage of being not\nonly gay and cheerful, but is suf\nficiently transparent so that the title\nmay be clearly seen through it.\nCardboard covered with bits of\ncloth, paper, leather, or oil cloth\nmakes a nice needle book, with a\nleaf or two of old flannel or woolen\ncloth.\nDust clothes are often such un\nsightly things that bright cheese\ncloth blanket stitched around the\nedges with contrasting yarn, make\ndusting far more fun.\nI'm sun1 you can find a board and\nfour wooden door-stops to make a\nfoot stool for grandfather. Paint the\nfeet and board his favorite color,\npaste on an appropriate picture (a\nhunting scene perhaps) and then\nshellac it.\n1-or sister who likes to entertain\nan attractive tray may be made by\nenameling a tin pie plate, paste on a\ngay picture, and then shellac it.\nThe penny match boxes which are\nthrown away b y tne dozen mane\ngood blocks for a small child. Fill\nthem with small stones, then cover\nthe box with cloth, or knitted strips\nof varying colors.\nAll the foregoing suggestions are\neasily made by small children with\nonly a little help from older members\nof the family and, being work of\ntheir own small hands, will be treas\nuied by those who receive them.\nBUSINESS IN PUTNAM\nDURING 1937 WAS GOOD\n(Continued From Page One)\nin many of the factories. The 1936\nfigure was only 3,044, two workers\nmore. The value of the manufactur\ned product from eight of the afore\nmentioned ten plants amounted dur\ning the year 1937, to well over $10,\n000,000.\nThe deposits in Putnam's three\nbanking houses, it will be noted,\ndropped from $10,776,649.05 in\n1936 to $10,006,976.92 this year. Of\ncourse this latter number may be in\ncreased before the close of business\ntomorrow night. However, it will be\nnoted that the drop came about, for\nthe most part, during the last two\nmonths. Up until that time, deposits\nhad been exceeding those of the\nprevious year. Bank loans, it was\nreported, were about the same this\nyear as during 1936.\nAlthough no figures were available\nat the Putnam post office, according\nto Postmaster Frank X Vadnais,\nbusiness there showed a slight in\ncrease during the past twelve\nmonths.\ni Building in Putnam in 1937 was,\nat times, brisk. The Common Coun\ncil granted permission for the erec\n1 tion of seven new homes within the\ncity limits. It also issued permits for\nthe erection of a garage, a service\nstation and a garage. Nine additions\nwere also allowed to be made by the\ncity during the period. Among the\noutstanding building projects of the\nyear in this section were: the addi\ntion to the Seder building on Main\n!street; the addition to the V. F. W\nHall on Main street; the building ot\nI a community House in North Gros\nvenordale; the building of a fire sta\nj tion on Woodstock Hill; the build\ning of several new homes; and the\nconstruction of a hangar at the State\nTrade School (this project has not\ni yet been completed).\nWEST WOODSTOCK\nMrs. Robert Johnson, Walter John\nson and Miss L. M. Perrin were in\nHartford Wednesday evening to en\njoy the Municipal Carol Sing at\nTimes Plana. The Plaza, beautifully\ndecorated made a grand back\nground for the singers and the\ntrumpeters in gay costumes. A huge\ni crowd of between 15,000 and 20,000\ngathered and joined in the singing\nThe Misses Alice Johnson and Betty\nPerrin were among the singers.\n1 culprit was caught, we can pic\nto Woodstock, with the legs\n1 tethered under the belly of th\nIt is not quite clear wha\n1 takes today. It still functions\nat which Judge Edward S.\nCounty Juvenile Court, was the\nstock Theft Detecting Society\nmobiles and tractors or what\n1 ciate it with its original purpo\n1 It carries the mind back to\nyoung and laying the foundai\nto the American tradition.\nLETTER TO THE EDITOR\nDuring the past year, 1 he Haver\nhas received donations from a num\nber of local people, aiding the work\nj Gifts of fruit, candy and tobacco\nwere received during the holiday)\nI from Mrs. Lefferts and Mrs I, Mor\nins Murray. Turkeys were donated\nby Mrs. Lefferts, Mrs. Bullard. Mrs\nStrong and Miss Wiggins. Lights and\nChristmas decorations were given by\nMrs. Bullard and Mrs. Strong.\nThe Sunshine Society from the\nPutnam Baptist church sent dowers\ni and remembrances to the home at\nChristmas. The holidays were bright\nened by carol singers from Pomfret\nSchool and the Congregational\nchurch of Putnam.\nThe Needle Work Guild of Brook\nlyn contributed generously with bed\n1 ding and wearing apparel in 1937. The\nMen\u2019s Club from the Baptist church\nin Danielson have conducted services\n1 at the Haven on the first Sunday of\nevery month. These services are\n1 mucn enjoyed by the old people.\nWe wish to express our gratitude\nto the many friends who have contrib\nuted to the Haven Fund of which\nMrs. T. Morris Murray is custodian.\nA total of $1.S40 has been received\nthrough donations. The money has\nbeen applied to the deficit caused by\nthe inability' of so many patients to\npay rates large enough to cover the\nactual operating expenses. Among\nthose who have contributed financial\nly to the Haven are: Mrs. Hughes,\nCaptain Goodhue, Miss Fuller, Mrs.\nLefferts, Miss Marion Harvey, Mr.\nVarnum. James Col pan, Mr. Roger\nClapp and Dr. Souther and Mrs. John\nGrosvenor.\nSUSAN J. GRIGGS,\nSuperintendent.\nGLADDING COW MAKES\nNEW OFFICIAL RECORD\nA new record, exceeding the\naverage of the Guernsey breed for\nher age and class has just been com\npleted by a three and one-half year\nold cow, Flora of Borrodale 374,051\nof Thompson, tested and owned by'\nEllen DeF. T. Gladding. Her official\nrecord supervised by the Connecti\ncut Agricultural College and an\nnounced by the American Guernsey\nCattle Club is 9,966.4 pounds of milk\nand 534.6 pounds of butter fat in\nclass DD.\nBowling\nCITY LEAGUE\nStanding of Teams For Week End\ning Dec. 25, 1937\nV' oodstock\nPutnam Woolen\nFranklins Amoco\nA. anti P.\nPom fret\nAttawaugan\nMontgomery Ward\nHanley's Gulf Prides\nPorter Dearington\nlerks\nHigh team total\u2014Putnam Woolen\n1,8 Id.\nWon Lost\n27 13\n2(3 14\n27 17\n26 18 I\n18 22\n18 22\n14 22\n13 27\n8 32\nHigh team sheet\u2014F. Amoco 669.\nHigh three strings\u2014Webster 447.\nHigh single\u2014Cristofori 175.\nHijfh average\u2014Maynard 125.\nSedond average\u2014Kittredge 123.\nThud average\u2014Arnold 121.\nFranklins Amoco\u2014Arnold 118\n121 138 377; A. Watson 104 114 114\n332; S. Franklin 94 111 88 293; F. 1\nFranklin 85 105 90 280; Carpenter\n121 104 93 318\u20141,600.\nClerks\u2014Belair 110 127 106 343;\nSchlageter 92 96 1 12 300; Alvord\n78 137 116 331; Brayton 87 1 1 it 108\n314; St. Onge 109 91 84 184\u20141,572.:\nA. and P.\u2014-Light 94 100 145 339;'\nZito 102 93 104 299; G. Sherman 96\n105 95 296; Danielson 114 111 116\n341; Sherman 102 90 126 318\u20141\n1,593.\nMontgomery Ward\u2014F. Webster\n111 102 100 313; Adams 125 91 82\n298; Saunders 98 106 120 324; Pas\nture 98 108 109 315; Webster 90\n108 134 332\u20141582.\nAttawaugan\u2014Lyons 84 107 95\n286; Tracv 114 93 112 319; Warren\n126 99 98 323; Szela 116 129 108\n353; Bishop 101 117 107 325\u2014\n1,606.\nPorter Dearington\u2014Audette 102'\n113 98 313; Carlage 81 77 83 241;\nDansereau 92 94 108 294; Kierys\n116 108 111 335; Kittredge 135 146\n153 434\u20141,617.\nPutnam Woolen\u2014Dempsey 144\n9ff 110 351; Leo 107 109 87 303;\nCristofori 99 112 137 348; Lam\naureux 114 123 131 368; Maynard\n133 113 133\u20141,749.\nPomfret\u2014Maher 107 108 91 306;\nBeverly 115 128 101 344; McCarthy\n107 87 122 316; Zeller 98 108 80\n286; Cotter 92 135 103 330\u20141,582.\nPUTNAM FINISHING\nStanding of Teams For Week End\ning Dec. 25, 1937\nWon Lost\nBlue 34 22\nWhite 29 27\nGreen 28 28\nRed 21 35\nHigh team total\u2014White 1,834.\nHigh team sheet\u2014Green 652.\nHigh three strings\u2014Phillips 419.\nHigh single\u2014Phillips 171.\nHigh average\u2014Phillips 112.\nSecond average\u2014A. Leduc 105.\nGreen\u2014A. Geddes 76 79 82 237;\nKirkpatric 82 85 88 255; A. Rondeau\nI 78 97 81 256; Hughes 83 101 83\n1267; A. Leduc 111 96 125 332;\nPhillips 118 116 107 341 1,688.\ni Red\u2014Moser 71 87 92 250; Mora\ni bito 80 93 101 274; Racine 91 89\n(87 267; G. Geddes 121 107 100 328;\nDepaulo 92 115 91 298; Rainey 94\n101 101 296\u20141.713.\nWhite\u2014Gessner 95 92 77 264;\nJankot 105 95 109 309: Segisser 95\n107 80 282; Tabler 1 oO 110 86 296;\nI^abonte 82 93 85 260; Belair 105 89\n92 286\u20141,697.\nBlue\u2014Baker 91 109 94 294; Mac\nMurray 106 107 96 309; Wheatley\n100 79 82 261; Martineau 75 91 80\n246;; V. Leduc 82 94 91 267; Glin\nski 99 98 87 284\u20141.661.\nLure the triumphant march back\nqf the crest-fallen horse thief\ne horse.\nt form of activities the society\nfor it held a meeting Tuesday\nDennis, head of the Windham\nspeaker. Of course, the Wood\nwould cover the theft of auto\nnot. However, we like to asso\nse of rounding up horse thieves,\nhe days when Woodstock was\nion of its splendid contribution\nLEGAL NOTICES\nADMINISTRATION ACCOUNT\nState of Connect tout. District of\nWoodstock. *s. Court of Probate, De\n!ceml'cr 23rd. 1937. Estate of Julia\nK. Pike, late of Woodstock. in said\nDistrict deceased. The Executor hav\ning exhibited hts administration ac\nIcount with said estate to this ourt\n.for allowance, it is ORDERED\u2014That\nthe 4th da> of January. 1938 at\ni 10:0(1 o'clock ui the forenoon. at the\nProbate Court in Woodstock, be and\nthe same is. assign,\\i tor a hearing\n|on the allowance of said administra\ntion account with said estate, and\nthis Court directs the Executor to\ncite ad persons interested therein to\nappear at said time and place, by pub\nlishing this order once in some news\npaper having a circulation in said\nDistrict, and by posting s copy on the\npublic sign post in the Town of W ood\nstock, where the deceased last dwelt.\nROBERT E. HARRIS. Judge. 52\nAPPLICATION TO SELL\nREAL ESTATE\nDistrict of Woodstock, ss. Court of\nProbate. December 24th, 19o(. Es\ntate of Carl Eckman. late of Wood\nstock, in said District, deceased. The\nExecutor having applied for an order\nauthorizing and empowering him to\nsell certain real estate belonging to\nsaid estate, as per application on file\nmore fully appears; ORDERED\u2014\nThat the 4th day of January, 1938\nat 9:30 o\u2019clock in the forenoon, at the\nCourt of Probate in Woodstock, be j\nand the same is assigned for a hear\ning on the foregoing application, and\nthis Court directs the Executor to\ncite all persons interested therein to\nappear at said time and place, by;\npublishing this order of notice once i\nin some newspaper having a circula-\ntion in said District, and by posting\na copy on the public sign-post in the\nTown of Woodstock, where the deceas- j\ned last dwelt, at least five days be- j\nfore said day of hearing, and return\nmake to this Court of the notice!\ngiven. ROBERT E. HARRIS, Judge.\nAPPLICATION TO SELL\nREAL ESTATE\nDistrict of Woodstock, ss. Court of\nProbate. December 24th. 1937. Es\ntate of Maria Eckman. late of Wood\nstock, in said District, deceased. The\nExecutor having: applied for an order\nauthorizing and empowering him to\nsell certain real estate belonging to\nsaid estate, as per application on file\nmore fully appears; ORDERED\u2014\nThat the 4th day of January, 1938 at\n9:00 o'clock in the forenoon, at the\nCourt of Probate in Woodstock, be\nand the same is assigned for a hear\ning on the foregoing application, and\nthis Court directs the Executor to\ncite all persons interested therein to\nappear at said timeTind place, by pub\nlishing this order of notice once in\nsome newspaper having a circulation\nin said District, and by posting a\ncopy on the public sign-post in the\nTown of Woodstock, where the de\nceased last dwelt, at least five days\nbefore said day of hearing, and re\nturn make to this Court of the notice\ngiven. ROBERT E. HARRIS, Judge.\n.V>\nORDER OF NOTICE\nDistrict of Putnam, ss. Court of\nProbate, December 28th. 1937. Es-!\nfate of Everett A. Davis, late of\nPutnam, in said District, deceased.\nErnestine I>. Franklin of Putnam,\nConn., Administratrix. The adminis\ntratrix having applied for an order\nauthorizing and empowering some dis\ninterested person to be appointed by\nsaid Court to sell certain real estate\nbelonging to said estate, as per ap\nplication on file more fully appears; i\nORDERED That the 4th day of'\nJanuary, 1938, at 10:00 o\u2019clock in the\nforenoon, at the Court of Probate in j\nPutnam be and the same is assigned I\nfor a hearing on said application,\nand this Court directs the Adminis-j\ntratrix to cite all persons interested\ntherein to appear at said time and\nplace, by publishing this order of\nnotice once in some newspaper hav\ning a circulation in ssaid District, and\nby postng a copy on the public sign\npost in the Town of Putnam, where\nthe deceased last dwelt, at least five\ndays before said day of hearing, and\nreturn make to this Court of the\nnotice given. HENRY N. BENOIT,\n\u2022Judge. 52\nORDER OF NOTICE\nDistrict of Woodstock, ss. Probate\nCourt, December 29th, A.D. 1937. Es-\ntate of Mary F. Southworth, late of\nWoodstock, Conn., in said District, j\ndeceased. Upon the application of'\nMary I. Wright, praying that an i\ninstrument in writing purporting to j\nbe the last will and testament of said\nMary F. Southworth, deceased, may\nbe proved, approved, allowed and ad-j\nmitted to probate as per application\non file more fully appears, it is OR-l\nDERED\u2014That said application be;\nheard and determined at the Probate\nOffice in Woodstock, in said District,\non the 4th day of January, A.D.\n1938, at 2:00 o\u2019clock in the after\nnoon; and that a public notice be\ngiven of the pendency of said applica\ntion and time and place of hearing\nthereon, by publishing a copy of this\norder in a newspaper having a cir\nculation in said District, and by post\ning a copy thereof, on the public\nsign-post in the town of W\u2019oodstock,\nin the said District, at least five days\nbefore said dav of hearing. ROB\nERT E. HARRIS, Judge. 52\nORDER OF NOTICE\nAt a Probate Court held at Thomp\nson, Connecticut, within and for the\nDistrict of Thompson, on the 29th day\nof December, 1937. Present, Fred\nA. Munyan. Judge. Estate of Ran\ndolph H. Chandler, late of Thomp\nson in said District, deceased. The\nUnited States Trust Company, of New\nYork City, New York, Trustee of a\ncertain trust estate created by the\nlast will and testament of said de\ncedent, having filed in this Court for\nallowance its annual accounting with\nsaid trust, it is ORDERED That\nthe 7th day of January, 1938, at 2:30\no\u2019clock in the afternoon, at the Pro\nbate Office in Thompson in said Dis\ntrict, be, and the same is assigned\nfor a hearing upon the allowance of\nsaid accounting; and that public\nnotice be given of this order by pub\nlishing a copy hereof once in a news\npaper having a circulation in said\nDistrict, at least five days before the\ntime herein assigned for a hearing.\nFRED A. MUNYAN, Judge. 52\nPACKERS\u2019 OUTLET\nU. S. COVERNMENT INSPECTED MEATS\n16\u00b0 FRONT STREET PUTNAM, CONN.\nTURKEYS noarntchyern \u00bb1c\nROASTING PORK ^Tfi\nFANCY FOWL\nFRESH SHOULDERS \u201c15c\nSQUIRE\u2019S PURE\nSAUSAGE MEAT 25c\nSmoked Shoulders 18c\nCHUCK ROASTS\nPOT ROASTSBONELESS 19c\nSIRLOIN STEAK SE\u2019\u201c\u25a0 25c\nCUBE STEAKS TENDER 23i\nORDER OF NOTICE\nAt a Prohate Court held at Thomp\nson, Connecticut, within and for the\nDistrict of Thompson, on the 29th day\nof December, 1937. Present, Fred\nA. Munyan, Judge. Estate of Wil\nliam Henry Chandler, late of Thomp\nson in said District, deceased. The\nUnited States Trust Company of New\nYork City, New York, trustee of a\ncertain trust estate created by the\nlast will and testament of said de\ncedent, having filed in this Court for\nallowance its annual account with\nsaid trust, it is ORDERED\u2014That the\n7th day of January, 1938 at 2:00\no\u2019clock in the afternoon, at the Pro\nbate Office in Thompson in said Dis\ntrict. be, and is hereby assigned for\na hearing upon the allowance of the\nsaid account; and that public notice\nbe given of this order by publishing\na copy hereof once in a newspaper\nhaving a circulation in said District,\nat least five days before the time\nherein assigned for a hearing. FRED\nA. MUNYAN, Judge. 52\nLIMITATION OF CLAIMS\nAt a Court of Probate held at Put\nnam. in and for the District of Put\nnam. on the 21st day of December,\n1937. Present, Henry N. Benoit,\nJudge. Estate of Fred D. Card, late\nof Putnam, in said District, deceased.\nLottie D. Card of Putnam, Conn.,\nAdministratrix. ORDERED\u2014-That six\nmonths from the date hereof be and\nthe same are hereby appointed and\nlimited for the creditors of said de\nceased to bring in their claims against\nsaid estate, and that the administra\ntrix of said estate cite said creditors of\nsaid deceased to bring in their claims\nwithin said time, by posting a notice\nto that effect on the public sign-post\nin said Town of Putnam, and by\npublishing the same in a newspaper\nhaving a circulation in'said District,\n\u25a0ind that due return be made. HENRY\nN. BENOIT, Judge. 52\nCard of Thanks\nWe wish to express our most sin\ncere thanks to the many friends and\nneighbors who rendered such timely\nassistance when our barn burned.\nMr. and Mrs. John Smith,\nPhoenixville, Conn.\nA pear-shaped pearl weighing 68\ngrains and worth $5,000 was picked\nup on an Australian beach by a diver\nwho went out \u201cfor a little exercise.\u201d\nNOTICE OF SALE OF LAND\nI District of Putnam, ss. Court of\nProbate, December 29th 1937. Es\nI tate of Joseph W. Miller, late of Put\nI nam, in said District deceased,\n1 Notice is hereby given that pursuant\nI to the order of said Court made on\nithe 14th day of December, 1937 s|]\nI the right title and interest which said\n1 deceased had at the time of his\ndeath in and to certain personal\nproperty consisting of a lunch cart\nand contents of equipment and sup\nplies now located at 67 Front street,\nPutnam, Connecticut, will he soid at\nprivate sale on the 6th day of Janu\nary, 1938 at 10:00 o\u2019clock in the\nforenoon. Sale to take place at\nthe office of A. Macdonald. Jr., 66\ni Main street, Putnam, Conn. Terms\nmade known at time of sale. ED\nWARD BRZUCH. Committee of the\nProbate Court of Putnam. 52\nLIQUOR PERMIT\nNOTICE OF APPLICATION\nThis is to give notice that I, N\u2019ar\neisse I. Ravenelle, of North Gros\nvenordale, (Thompson) Conn., have\nfiled an application dated December\n28th, 1937 with the Liquor Control\nCommission for a Tavern Permit for\nthe sale of alcoholic liquor on the\npremises. Main street. North Grosven\nordale, (Thompson) Conn. The busi\nness is owned by Dora Ravenelle of\nI North Grosvenordale, (Thompson)\nConn., and will be conducted by N\u2019ar\ncisse I. Ravenelle of North Grosvenor\ndale, (Thompson) Conn., as permittee.\nNARC1SSE I. RAVENELLE.\nDated December 28th, 1937. 52-1\nCard of Thanks\nMr. and Mrs. Ozias Milligan and\nfamily wish to express their appre\nciation to the Muddy Brook Fire De\npartment the Woodstock olunteer\nFire Association and the newly or\nganized Bungay Fire Brigade for\ntheir speedy and thorough work in\nextinguishing the raging fire in their\nhome and store building, North Wood\nstock, early last Thursday morning.\nAlso to neighbors for care and shel\nter during the fire and for many\ngifts and kind acts from the church\nsociety and others, and work in tear\ning down and cleaning up after the\nfire freely given.\n1\nO^ASSlFffiD ADVERTISEWENTS 1\nA Clearing House For Those Who Have Some\nthing to Dispose Of and Those Wishing to Acquire\nSomething; For Employer and Employee; It Brings\nBuyer and Seller Together.\nFOR RENT\nFOR RENT\u2014Apartment, 6 rooms, 2\nporches and sunparlor. Hardwood\nfloors, porcelain sink, steam heat.\nApply at 165 CHURCH STREET}\nor telephone 983-3 Putnam, Conn.\n49tf\nFOR RENT\u20146-room apartment with\nhath, all modern improvements, I\nrent reasonable, at 149 Mechanics:\ns